[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":271},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Ftypescript\u002F2019\u002F06\u002F22\u002Fts-fundamentals-type-inference\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Ftypescript\u002F2019\u002F06\u002F22\u002Fts-fundamentals-type-inference\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Ftypescript\u002F2019\u002F06\u002F22\u002Fts-fundamentals-type-inference\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Ftypescript\u002F2019\u002F06\u002F22\u002Fts-fundamentals-type-inference\u002F":246,"related:\u002Fen\u002Ftypescript\u002F2019\u002F06\u002F22\u002Fts-fundamentals-type-inference\u002F":255},"\u002FTypeScript\u002F20190622\u002F2739569432\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":8,"body":9,"category":228,"date":229,"description":230,"extension":231,"lang":232,"meta":233,"navigation":234,"path":235,"readingMinutes":236,"seo":237,"standalone":238,"stem":239,"tags":240,"tldr":243,"updated":229,"url":244,"__hash__":245},"content\u002Fen\u002FTypeScript\u002Fts-fundamentals-type-inference.md","TypeScript Fundamentals — Type Inference","8586083489","\u002Ftypescript\u002F20190622\u002F2739569432\u002F",{"type":10,"value":11,"toc":223},"minimark",[12,17,31,35,38,42,45,78,81,112,115,122,125,141,144,169,172,206,213,219],[13,14,16],"h2",{"id":15},"intro","Intro",[18,19,20,21,25,26,30],"p",{},"Last post we covered how to set variable types in TypeScript. I mentioned at the end that TypeScript still compiles if you don't annotate — but is that ",[22,23,24],"em",{},"really"," the case? This post covers a cool TypeScript feature called ",[27,28,29],"strong",{},"type inference",": even without explicit annotations, TypeScript can figure out the type.",[13,32,34],{"id":33},"whats-type-inference","What's type inference?",[18,36,37],{},"Pretty simple — if you don't explicitly tell TypeScript a variable's type, TypeScript infers it from the value you assigned. In English this is \"Type Inference\". Let's look at an example.",[13,39,41],{"id":40},"example","Example",[18,43,44],{},"This declaration has no type annotation, but TypeScript is fine with it:",[46,47,52],"pre",{"className":48,"code":49,"language":50,"meta":51,"style":51},"language-ts shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","let man = 'Ray';\n","ts","",[53,54,55],"code",{"__ignoreMap":51},[56,57,60,64,68,71,75],"span",{"class":58,"line":59},"line",1,[56,61,63],{"class":62},"sWyjQ","let",[56,65,67],{"class":66},"sMAXC"," man ",[56,69,70],{"class":62},"=",[56,72,74],{"class":73},"sTRMh"," 'Ray'",[56,76,77],{"class":66},";\n",[18,79,80],{},"But what about this?",[46,82,84],{"className":48,"code":83,"language":50,"meta":51,"style":51},"let man = 'Ray';\nman = 10;\n",[53,85,86,98],{"__ignoreMap":51},[56,87,88,90,92,94,96],{"class":58,"line":59},[56,89,63],{"class":62},[56,91,67],{"class":66},[56,93,70],{"class":62},[56,95,74],{"class":73},[56,97,77],{"class":66},[56,99,101,104,106,110],{"class":58,"line":100},2,[56,102,103],{"class":66},"man ",[56,105,70],{"class":62},[56,107,109],{"class":108},"sCcAr"," 10",[56,111,77],{"class":66},[18,113,114],{},"You get an error:",[18,116,117],{},[118,119],"img",{"alt":120,"src":121},"Wrong type","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FXHiu6DW.png",[18,123,124],{},"Why? Because when you don't provide a type, TypeScript infers it from the initial value. So even though your code says:",[46,126,127],{"className":48,"code":49,"language":50,"meta":51,"style":51},[53,128,129],{"__ignoreMap":51},[56,130,131,133,135,137,139],{"class":58,"line":59},[56,132,63],{"class":62},[56,134,67],{"class":66},[56,136,70],{"class":62},[56,138,74],{"class":73},[56,140,77],{"class":66},[18,142,143],{},"TypeScript actually sees it as:",[46,145,147],{"className":48,"code":146,"language":50,"meta":51,"style":51},"let man:string = 'Ray';\n",[53,148,149],{"__ignoreMap":51},[56,150,151,153,156,159,162,165,167],{"class":58,"line":59},[56,152,63],{"class":62},[56,154,155],{"class":66}," man",[56,157,158],{"class":62},":",[56,160,161],{"class":108},"string",[56,163,164],{"class":62}," =",[56,166,74],{"class":73},[56,168,77],{"class":66},[18,170,171],{},"That's how TypeScript helps you avoid weird issues. But what if you don't assign a value at all?",[46,173,175],{"className":48,"code":174,"language":50,"meta":51,"style":51},"let man;\nman = 10;\nman = '123';\n",[53,176,177,184,194],{"__ignoreMap":51},[56,178,179,181],{"class":58,"line":59},[56,180,63],{"class":62},[56,182,183],{"class":66}," man;\n",[56,185,186,188,190,192],{"class":58,"line":100},[56,187,103],{"class":66},[56,189,70],{"class":62},[56,191,109],{"class":108},[56,193,77],{"class":66},[56,195,197,199,201,204],{"class":58,"line":196},3,[56,198,103],{"class":66},[56,200,70],{"class":62},[56,202,203],{"class":73}," '123'",[56,205,77],{"class":66},[18,207,208,209,212],{},"TypeScript won't infer this time — it'll default the type to ",[53,210,211],{},"any",". But I'd strongly recommend not doing this. It's a great way to get unpredictable bugs.",[18,214,215],{},[118,216],{"alt":217,"src":218},"any type","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FP7wDAjh.png",[220,221,222],"style",{},"html pre.shiki code .sWyjQ, html code.shiki .sWyjQ{--shiki-default:#FF9492}html pre.shiki code .sMAXC, html code.shiki .sMAXC{--shiki-default:#F0F3F6}html pre.shiki code .sTRMh, html code.shiki .sTRMh{--shiki-default:#ADDCFF}html .default .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html pre.shiki code .sCcAr, html code.shiki .sCcAr{--shiki-default:#91CBFF}",{"title":51,"searchDepth":100,"depth":100,"links":224},[225,226,227],{"id":15,"depth":100,"text":16},{"id":33,"depth":100,"text":34},{"id":40,"depth":100,"text":41},"TypeScript","2019-06-22 15:49:05","Last post mentioned that TypeScript still compiles even if you skip type annotations — but is that really the case? This post covers a really important TypeScript feature called type inference.","md","en",{},true,"\u002Fen\u002Ftypescript\u002Fts-fundamentals-type-inference","1",{"title":6,"description":230},false,"en\u002FTypeScript\u002Fts-fundamentals-type-inference",[241,242,228],"TypeScript Fundamentals","JavaScript",null,"\u002Fen\u002Ftypescript\u002F2019\u002F06\u002F22\u002Fts-fundamentals-type-inference\u002F","j3nUb0xPuKZC0p-N6dNM0wbWHab4iFgq1l50DAFwmjc",{"newer":247,"older":251},{"url":248,"title":249,"date":250},"\u002Fen\u002Ftypescript\u002F2019\u002F06\u002F22\u002Fts-fundamentals-union-types\u002F","TypeScript Fundamentals — Union Types","2019-06-22 21:56:38",{"url":252,"title":253,"date":254},"\u002Fen\u002Ftypescript\u002F2019\u002F06\u002F22\u002Fts-fundamentals-variables\u002F","TypeScript Fundamentals — Variables","2019-06-22 15:06:22",[256,261,266],{"url":257,"title":258,"date":259,"readingMinutes":260},"\u002Fen\u002Ftypescript\u002F2024\u002F09\u002F30\u002Ftypescript-generics-and-vue3-generics\u002F","Getting Comfortable With TypeScript Generics (and Vue 3 Generics)","2024-09-30 17:31:32","4",{"url":262,"title":263,"date":264,"readingMinutes":265},"\u002Fen\u002Ftypescript\u002F2023\u002F12\u002F15\u002Fwhy-use-typescript-superset-explained\u002F","A Casual Chat About TypeScript — What It Is and Why Use It","2023-12-15 10:17:49","10",{"url":267,"title":268,"date":269,"readingMinutes":270},"\u002Fen\u002Ftypescript\u002F2019\u002F06\u002F23\u002Fts-fundamentals-classes\u002F","TypeScript Fundamentals — Classes","2019-06-23 11:43:56","3",1784010292945]